general_comment:
Congratulations on finishing the project :fireworks:!!

There are many great additional resources for learning HTML online. Here is a list of a few of the best:

- [MDN's guide to HTML][1].
- [MDN's guide to HTML Elements][2].
- [Udacity's Style Guide for HTML][3].
- [W3 HTML Validator][4].
- [HTML5 specification][5] - which is not a bad place to learn HTML really.

It is especially useful to use the HTML validator, as it checks your HTML and makes sure there are no errors.

Keep up the good work.

[1]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML
[2]: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element
[3]: https://udacity.github.io/frontend-nanodegree-styleguide/
[4]: https://validator.w3.org/nu/#textarea
[5]: https://www.w3.org/TR/html5/

:information_source: Remember to open the Code Review tab to check out the review comments! You can also get there by clicking the button at the bottom of the page:

rubric.description:
Practice HTML syntax by converting a mockup of a blog article into a real website!

### Project Submission

* Take a moment to double check that your `index.html` file renders *exactly* like the mockup! You do not have to match the margins (spacing along the sides) of the mockup.
* Make sure you've answered all the questions for the reflection. Feel free to use your native language! Graders will translate if necessary.
* Check your project against the **[Project Rubric](https://review.udacity.com/#!/projects/7359899771/rubric)**.
* Create and submit a zip file containing `index.html` and `reflections.txt`.

Good luck! I know that you can do it 🚀
